<h2>Event in March 2018</h2>
<h3>Low temperatures mid-March</h3>
For the second time since the sudden warming of the stratosphere in February, there was a typical cold-air outflow in Central Europe, just before the astronomical start of spring on 21 March.
An area of ​​high pressure shifted from Svalbard to Scandinavia, where surface pressure increased to more than 1035 hPa on 16 March. In Northwest Russia there was still very cold air present which was advected to Central and Western Europe. Also the temperatures in the upper atmosphere were relatively low which permitted the development of convective precipitation including snow.
In some areas from Germany to the UK, snowfall and snow drift occurred and even a frost period of a couple of days was reported in Central Europe. Deutschneudorf-Brüderwiese at 688 m height recorded at night a minimum temperature of -17.1 &#176;C on 19 March.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/mar2018/20180320pic10.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/mar2018/20180320pic10.jpg" width="350px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Satellite image showing the eastern flow over Central Europe. Note the break-up in clouds causing very low minimum temperatures in Poland and Germany. Source: NASA/MODIS.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for March 2018</h2>
<br><br>
March was characterized by two cold waves, one at the beginning and the other in the third week of the month. Central and Eastern Europe had in March 12-20 days with frost. Large parts of Northern Europe had almost every night frost, while Southern and Southwestern Europe had much less frost days (Figure 2, days with minimum temperature below 0&#176;C).
